      <tr><td colspan=1  style='font-size: 9.5px;'>86 threads, <a href=journal.html?user=91720&start=0>1</a> <a href=journal.html?user=91720&start=25>2</a> <a href=journal.html?user=91720&start=50>3</a> <a href=journal.html?user=91720&start=75>4</a>  page(s) long</td><td  style='font-size: 9.5px;' align=right>&nbsp;<a href=journal.html?user=91720&start=25>Next Page</a></td></tr></table></form><ul><table  border=0 cellpadding=2 cellspacing=0 awidth=100%><a name=102281534397975></a><form action=http://eqdb.allakhazam.com/strategy/mrate.pl name=f102281534397975><tr><td id=headerrow><a id=sj href=journal.html?user=91720&mid=102281534397975>Epic</a> <a id=fs8 href=journal.html?user=91720&mid=102281534397975#post><img src=http://everquest.allakhazam.com/static/reply.gif border=0 alt="Reply..." height=16 width=16></a></td><td align=right id=headerrow valign=bottom><span id=notbold>By:</span> <a href=poster.html?user=91720><span id= >roshi the Charming</span></a>, <span id= > </span><br><span id=notbold>119 posts</td></tr>
	   <tr><td colspan=1 id=headerrow>Posted @ Thu, May 30th 11:32 PM 2002</td>
	   <td id=headerrow align=right><span id=notbold>Score</span>: Decent<span id=notbold>[2.50]</span></td></tr>
	   <tr><td colspan=2>Nostalgic Gaming part one: Epic MegaGames.<br><br>Jazz Jack Rabbit, Jill of the Jungle, One Must Fall 2097, Epic Pinball, ZZT; What do all these games have in common. They are all good games made by one company, Epic Megagames, better known as the original developer of Unreal(a great game in its own right) before they were bought out. Well before Unreal, Epic, along with Apogee, were the kings of shareware. For those of you who don’t know what shareware is, its very simple. Lets take Jill of the Jungle for example. Jill of the Jungle had 3 parts, the first part was free, hence the share, and the rest of it you could only play if you paid for it. Not quite a demo because most shareware was fun and long even without registering. <br>	So epic turned out game after game, sure it had turds, but who doesn’t. But what I remember most about the shareware days was that they turned out some groundbreaking classics. Epic Pinball I consider to be the best pinball simulation of all time. ZZT, even with its ACII characters, was load of fun because you could create your own game. OMF 2097 is the best PC fighting game PERIOD. Epic turned out great games even though they were not full copies, hence doing more with less. I was fortunate enough to live a few minutes from their studios, so I got my hands on full copies of certain games(I still have the cds of epic pinball and Jazz jackrabbit too) and the full games even more cemented my respect for them. These games still stand the test of time as true classics that still are as fun today as they were when they came out, even with the technological advancement.&nbsp;&nbsp;But where are they now? Nowhere really. With all the hype of Unreal they dumped all their old franchises to work on it and then got bough out by DMA design, which in turn got bought out by Infrogames.. All is not lost though; an updated version of OMF is coming soon. There is also adventure pinball, a cousin of epic pinball, released last year. Jazz Jackrabbit had a sequel but was kind of under the radar. The epic Pinball team helped form diversions entertainment that is working on unreal 2. Jill of the Jungle is unfortunately, dead. R.I.P Jill and pray some game company updates you.<br>Next time, Part two, Old school adventure games.<br><br><br>&nbsp;<br></td></tr>
