<table  border=0 cellpadding=2 cellspacing=0 awidth=100%><a name=102225056560333></a><form action=http://eqdb.allakhazam.com/strategy/mrate.pl name=f102225056560333><tr><td id=headerrow><a id=sj href=journal.html?user=91720&mid=102225056560333>SKill based</a> <a id=fs8 href=journal.html?user=91720&mid=102225056560333#post><img src=http://everquest.allakhazam.com/static/reply.gif border=0 alt="Reply..." height=16 width=16></a></td><td align=right id=headerrow valign=bottom><span id=notbold>By:</span> <a href=poster.html?user=91720><span id= >roshi the Charming</span></a>, <span id= > </span><br><span id=notbold>119 posts</td></tr>
	   <tr><td colspan=1 id=headerrow>Posted @ Fri, May 24th 10:39 AM 2002</td>
	   <td id=headerrow align=right><span id=notbold>Score</span>: Decent<span id=notbold>[2.50]</span></td></tr>
	   <tr><td colspan=2>Hello well I am starting a final series of rants leading up to when Crayon Alley goes up and this journal goes down. I am currently figuring out how to make the comic and can’t do much without a scanner, which I will buy this weekend.&nbsp;&nbsp;Anyway the final series of rants focus on topics I wanted to do but never actually got around to doing. This week is the myth of skill-based superiority. Enjoy.<br><br>What do EQ, AO and DAOC all have in common? They are level based games. While AO is a more of a highbred, it still has levels. Now in level based games, there exists a leveling treadmill, where you whack, whack, whack all day and gain levels. People don’t like leveling treadmills so much, so they scream for skill-based games. Some how they think that by removing levels they remove the treadmill. Therefore people will spend times doing other stuff such as quests and socializing. WRONG!! All you do is create a skills treadmill. I didn’t play UO, but from what I heard, people whacked away all day to up skills as well. See now instead of whacking so all your skills go up, now your whacking so only one or two goes up. The treadmill still remains its just skills and not levels. Take SW:G, do you really think people won’t spend many hours just on one skill by doing one thing, your kidding yourself. Also people spend plenty of time doing quests and socializing in level based games. Some people spend so much time socializing or questing, they don’t level up fast.<br>What needs to change is game design. If the game is designed for camping spots, it does not matter what the game uses for personal advancement.  Level based games can work; they work for D&amp;D and can work for MMORPGS. The game needs to designed with a story-line like flow with fluid environments they players can interact in. DAOC has the right idea, but it was too level based. Another thing you can do is make levels mean less, which games AC do. As for skill-based games, they are good too, but not the Holy Grail people expect them to be. Any system can work, it’s the game design that matters.<br><br>Roshi Out.<br><br>&nbsp;<br></td></tr>
