<table  border=0 cellpadding=2 cellspacing=0 awidth=100%><a name=101742210827445></a><form action=http://eqdb.allakhazam.com/strategy/mrate.pl name=f101742210827445><tr><td id=headerrow><a id=sj href=journal.html?user=91720&mid=101742210827445>Guild leadership</a> <a id=fs8 href=journal.html?user=91720&mid=101742210827445#post><img src=http://everquest.allakhazam.com/static/reply.gif border=0 alt="Reply..." height=16 width=16></a></td><td align=right id=headerrow valign=bottom><span id=notbold>By:</span> <a href=poster.html?user=91720><span id= >roshi the Charming</span></a>, <span id= > </span><br><span id=notbold>119 posts</td></tr>
	   <tr><td colspan=1 id=headerrow>Posted @ Fri, Mar 29th 12:19 PM 2002</td>
	   <td id=headerrow align=right><span id=notbold>Score</span>: Decent<span id=notbold>[2.50]</span></td></tr>
	   <tr><td colspan=2>&nbsp;&nbsp;     This week I am going philosophical, I am going to talk about “what is guild leadership” For the past weeks I have caught myself in an Alliance of two guilds, Division 3, an uber-like rp guild run military vets; and Black Valley, a rather small guild run by an acquaintance of mine. I first joined Div3, after two hellish weeks, I left and tried to join B.V, well it was not as easy as I though It was, but it got me thinking on leadership. Enjoy.<br><br>Leadership, to be successful, has to be earned. It is not some inalienable right given to you by virtue of being a guild officer or by birth in the case of monarchies. The only way for people to listen to you is by earning their trust and respect. If you do not earn their respect, then you are doomed. This applies in real-life as in guilds. Many guilds I have been in have fallen due to in-effectual leaders, who try to act like leaders even though their underlings do not trust them.  <br><br>Now, division 3’s leaders earned their power through being appointed there, even though as leaders many of them fail. In order to correct that, they have set up as series of strict rules that must be obeyed to keep order. This is what keeps them in power. However, rules are only as powerful as the leaders behind them.  If they have not earned their respect and leadership, rules are hard to enforce.  Its does not matter how forceful you are to enforce them; if you are not a true leader you will fail. A true guild leader does not need a large strict set of rules to keep order (this does necessarily apply to real-life, however). <br><br>I had a conversation on Wednesday with Black Valley’s leader. In that conversation, the main sticking point was will I follow 100% percent of her orders if let in. I basically said yes, because she has earned my trust and respect. She is putting me through as test to see that, that is fine because I respect her and will follow her rules. I left Div3 because I was forced to obey rules and orders from people who I saw as not true leaders. I now realize that I once failed as a guild officer in a previous guild in EQ because I failed to earn the respect of the people I was leading. Feel to argue with me on this, but keep in mind, I am philosophy major so I am good at these debates.<br><br>Roshi Out.<br><br>&nbsp;<br></td></tr>
