	   <tr><td colspan=2>Roshi’s rants will continue on, this can be good or bad depending on your view of the SOLE regularly updated non-Everquest related journal on this site. <br><br>Anyways this week I am going to talk about why I think Avatars-Offline a new documentary about MMORPG players is disturb- Oh wait scrap that, I am one and I devote some time every week writing about it, but who cares. Well anyways back to what I was saying, I think it disturbing because it paints MMORPG players as people who basically go online and forget about the real world. Oh, wait,&nbsp;&nbsp;do that, ok lets change my point of view. I think it will be a very interesting film because MMORPG changes people’s lives. <br>	For example, lets take my dad. He is a fifty-five year old layer for the government. He loves his kids, my stepmother and from the looks of it, a very normal guy. However he is an ever-quest addict, and in some ways, a worse addict than me. For example, he missed the lighting of my birthday cake a few weeks ago because he was going on Plane of Hate raid and then continued to play for about 10 more hours after that. He has taken of numerous days from work in order to gain another level. I have not done nor I will ever do such things because I value things like having a life. <br>This is the kind of fanaticism this movie will probably explore. I think it is important to look at why people will go to suck lengths for the sake of a virtual avatar. Even-though I am an AO addict (somewhat anyway), I cannot begin to fathom the mindsets of some of the people I meet online. I think this movie will be very interesting, I just wonder when its coming out.<br>Roshi out.<br>P.S. go to <a href="http://www.avatarsoffline.com" target=_new>http://www.avatarsoffline.com</a><br> and go to the who page and scroll down aways to see what some of your “favorite” develops look like. I cannot look at another Tweety rant the same way ever again. <br><br><br><em id=fs8>Edited, Thu Feb 28 22:57:24 2002</em><br>&nbsp;<br></td></tr>
