sacrificial lamb, during the court action against Microsoft.  But, frankly, if he expressed the opinion that he hates the public, who could blame him after the grief he has been on the receiving end of?<br><br><i>The only really successful businessman I can think of, who's genuinely popular, is Richard Branson.  (He's English, so I don't know how well known he is un the US.)</i><br><br>In general, to be successful, requires hardness and the ability to make unpopular decisions.  And this doesn't lead to popularity.  Therefore, the head of a company is not going to be popular.  And it's far more efficient, to let the company's image to be built by style analysts.<br><br>That's all you have anywhere.  Where it seems that the CEO is part of a nice cosy image, it's just a fake anyway!<br><br>Anyhow, it looks like it's my turn to be cynical, while you're not.  That's basically all I have to say.<br><br>See ya in Norrath.<br><br>AlAaraaf.<br><br>&nbsp;<br>"Te aurdire no possum. Musa sapienum fixa est in aura."</td></tr>
